Technical Specification: Kinetic Mesh & Chromatic Hadron Substrate
Assignee: Continuity Collective, LLC
Standard Compliance: USPTO DOCX; NIST FIPS 180-4; IEEE 1063-2001
I. Title of the Invention
Distributed Multi-Spectral Laser Logic & Kinetic Mesh Communication Substrate
II. Background of the Invention
Existing communication substrates suffer from a ~30% refractive latency in fiber optics and significant packet-loss in non-line-of-sight RF environments. Standard A.I. architectures rely on centralized "Cloud" models that introduce a "Handshake Gap," preventing real-time 0.001 precision in distributed tactical maneuvers.
III. Brief Summary of the Invention
The present invention comprises a dual-medium communication architecture utilizing IRIS-coded 8-spectrum laser modulation for backbone backhaul and SDR-integrated MANET (Mobile Ad-hoc Network) for terminal distribution. The core logic utilizes Proprietary Geometric Temporal Shifting of pulses across a 3x to 6x depth scale to shape the Hadron Chromatic data travel.
IV. Detailed Description of the Preferred Embodiment
This section defines the "Logic Current" and physical hardware interface required for Mission #1: Homeless Hope.
1. The Chromatic Encoder (IRIS)
The IRIS encoder modulates a 1550 nm SWIR laser across eight discrete spectral bands.
 * Geometric Shift: Pulses are deformed along the temporal axis based on the Cycler Shale coordinates.
 * Depth Scaling: Data density is bifurcated into depth-tiers (3x to 6x), allowing for simultaneous high-fidelity logic and biometric telemetry.
2. The Distributed GNU Processing Array
Node-level computation utilizes GNU Parallel to execute SHA-512 integrity checks on incoming 1B token packets.
 * Telemetry Bounce: The node measures the differential between predicted state and kinetic return, applying an Offset Correction in real-time.
V. Claims (The Legal Boundary)
 * A method for distributed logic stabilization comprising:
   * Generating an 8-color multispectral laser pulse;
   * Applying a Geometric Temporal Shift at 3x to 6x depth;
   * Anchoring said pulse via SHA-512 provenance at a mobile Nokia/Cisco hub.
 * The system of claim 1, further comprising a MANET ground mesh utilizing RF Dielectric Sensors for moisture-penetrating signal integrity.
